{"title_page": "Martin Pinehas", "text_new": "{{BLP self-published|section|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Martin Kambulu Pinehas\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|11|11}}\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| birth_place   = [[Ondangwa]], [[Namibia]]\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{NAM}}\n| branch        = Namibian Air Force\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[Air Marshal]]\n| servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n| unit          = \n| commands      = {{plainlist |\n*Commander of the Namibian Air Force<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/pdfs/mutwa%20profile.pdf {{dead link|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = {{plainlist |\n*Excellent Order of the Eagle, third Class\n}}\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n\n'''Martin Kambulu Pinehas''' is a Namibian military officer who is serving as the Chief of the Defence Force<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/geingob-appoints-pinehas-as-cdf</ref>, he previously served as Commander of the [[Namibian Air Force]]. He was appointed the Commander of the Air wing of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] in 2000. He has over 3700 flight hours of experience, including 700 as an instructor.\n\n==Military Career==\nPinehas joined [[SWAPO]]'s armed wing in 1980 and was deployed to the  Cadet Military Academy in Cuba which he completed in 1981.<ref name=\"gov.na\"/> He was then sent for jet flying training in [[Libya]] in 1984. His career in the Namibian Defence Force started in 1993 after Namibia's independence when he was inducted with the rank of [[Captain]]. In 1994 he was appointed as the Commanding Officer of the 1st Air Wing squadron with the rank of Major. in 1998 he was promoted to the rank of Lieutenant Colonel and appointed as the Chief of Staff of the Air Wing. In 2000 he was promoted to Colonel and appointed as Air Wing Commander. In 2002 he was appointed as  Air Force Commander and rising through the ranks of Brigadier General until Air Vice-marshall which he was bestowed in 2008.<ref name=\"gov.na\">{{cite web|last1=Pinehas|first1=Martin|title=Auto Biography for Air Force Commander|url=http://www.mod.gov.na/documents/264813/286599/profile+of+AF+Commander.pdf/2577c71a-4a03-41f0-8ad2-e02411c6da30}}</ref> He has a Master of Business Administration Degree and a Bachelor of Commerce Degree at Regent Business School, and has undergone several military and aviation training in Namibia and abroad. \n\nHe received from President Pohamba in 2014;[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Namibia|The Excellent Order of the Eagle: Third Class]], [[Heroes' Day (Namibia)|Heroes' Day]] 2014<ref>{{Cite news | title=Namibians honoured by President | newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]] | date= 28 August 2014 | url=http://www.newera.com.na/2014/08/28/namibians-honoured-by-president/}}</ref>. On the  31 March 2020 He was promoted to Air Marshal And appointed as Chief of Defence Force becoming the first non Army General to occupy the position.\n\n==Honours and Awards==\n* Meritorious Service Medal\n* [[File:M\u00e9rito Santos Dumont.png|x20px]]  Santos-Dumont Merit Medal\n* Order of Eagle 3rd Class Medal\n\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[John Mutwa]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Chief of the Defence Force (Namibia)|Chief of Defence Force]]\n| years = 1 April 2020 {{snd}}incumbent\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Incumbent\n\n}}{{s-bef\n| before = Vacant\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Commander [[Namibian Air Force]]\n| years = 2002{{snd}} 31 March 2020\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = \n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinehas, Martin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Namibian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Air marshals]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP self-published|section|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Martin Kambulu Pinehas\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|11|11}}\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| birth_place   = [[Ondangwa]], [[Namibia]]\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{NAM}}\n| branch        = Namibian Air Force\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[Air Marshal]]\n| servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n| unit          = \n| commands      = {{plainlist |\n*Commander of the Namibian Air Force<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/pdfs/mutwa%20profile.pdf {{dead link|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = {{plainlist |\n*Excellent Order of the Eagle, third Class\n}}\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n\n'''Martin Kambulu Pinehas''' is a Namibian military officer who is serving as the Chief of the Defence Force<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/geingob-appoints-pinehas-as-cdf</ref>, he previously served as Commander of the [[Namibian Air Force]]. He was appointed the Commander of the Air wing of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] in 2000. He has over 3700 flight hours of experience, including 700 as an instructor.\n\n==Military Career==\nPinehas joined [[SWAPO]]'s armed wing in 1980 and was deployed to the  Cadet Military Academy in Cuba which he completed in 1981.<ref name=\"gov.na\"/> He was then sent for jet flying training in [[Libya]] in 1984. His career in the Namibian Defence Force started in 1993 after Namibia's independence when he was inducted with the rank of [[Captain]]. In 1994 he was appointed as the Commanding Officer of the 1st Air Wing squadron with the rank of Major. in 1998 he was promoted to the rank of Lieutenant Colonel and appointed as the Chief of Staff of the Air Wing. In 2000 he was promoted to Colonel and appointed as Air Wing Commander. In 2002 he was appointed as  Air Force Commander and rising through the ranks of Brigadier General until Air Vice-marshall which he was bestowed in 2008.<ref name=\"gov.na\">{{cite web|last1=Pinehas|first1=Martin|title=Auto Biography for Air Force Commander|url=http://www.mod.gov.na/documents/264813/286599/profile+of+AF+Commander.pdf/2577c71a-4a03-41f0-8ad2-e02411c6da30}}</ref> He has a Master of Business Administration Degree and a Bachelor of Commerce Degree at Regent Business School, and has undergone several military and aviation training in Namibia and abroad. \n\nHe received from President Pohamba in 2014;[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Namibia|The Excellent Order of the Eagle: Third Class]], [[Heroes' Day (Namibia)|Heroes' Day]] 2014<ref>{{Cite news | title=Namibians honoured by President | newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]] | date= 28 August 2014 | url=http://www.newera.com.na/2014/08/28/namibians-honoured-by-president/}}</ref>. On the  31 March 2020 He was promoted to Air Marshal And appointed as Chief of Defence Force becoming the first non Army General to occupy the position.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[John Mutwa]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Chief of the Defence Force (Namibia)|Chief of Defence Force]]\n| years = 1 April 2020 {{snd}}incumbent\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Incumbent\n\n}}{{s-bef\n| before = Vacant\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Commander [[Namibian Air Force]]\n| years = 2002{{snd}} 31 March 2020\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = \n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinehas, Martin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Namibian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Air marshals]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Pinehas"}
{"title_page": "Elizabeth Callaghan", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Callaghan''' (1802-1852; also '''Eliza Thompson''',<ref name=Brown /> later '''Elizabeth Batman''' and '''Sarah Willoughby''') was a [[Convicts in Australia|convict]] born in [[Ireland]] in 1802 and shipped to the penal colony in [[New South Wales]] at the age of 17 for passing a [[counterfeit]] bank note for [[Banknotes of the pound sterling|\u00a3]]1 with intent to [[defraud]] the [[Bank of England]].<ref name=\"poi-australia.com.au\">{{cite web|url = http://poi-australia.com.au/eliza-batman-nee-callaghan/|title = Eliza Batman (n\u00e9e Callaghan)|work = POI Australia|accessdate = 16 November 2015}}</ref> She travelled with 103 other convicts on 6 June 1821 and arrived in [[Hobart]] on 7 January 1822.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Convict Records: Elizabeth Callaghan|url = http://www.convictrecords.com.au/convicts/callaghan/elizabeth/93261|website = www.convictrecords.com.au|accessdate = 2015-11-17}}</ref><ref name=Brown>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=P.L.|title=Batman, John (1801\u20131839)|date=1966|publisher=Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|location=Melbourne|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/batman-john-1752/text1947|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> The town of [[Mount Eliza, Victoria|Mount Eliza]] near [[Melbourne]] is named after her.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n== Early life ==\nCallaghan had roots in [[Ennis]], [[County Clare]], Ireland. She worked as a servant.<ref name=\"founder\">{{cite web|url=http://www.founders-storylines.com/mugsheets/convicts/profile/1126/elizabeth_callaghan|title=Elizabeth CALLAGHAN|work=founders-storylines.com|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> It has been said that her family of origin were land owners and her grandfather of exceptional wealth. There appears to be some separation of Elizabeth\u2019s father from her grandparents and suggestions that her father was a very unhappy man. Her mother was an elegant, learned and strong lady of exceptional [[character structure|character]]. The family struggled, and Callaghan was sent on her way at just seventeen.  Beautiful, elegant, fiery and learned \u2013 her mother was confident that she would easily find her place in the world.<ref name=\"poi-australia.com.au\"/>\n\n== Criminal record ==\n[[File:\u00a31 Gloucester Old Bank note for Charles Evans & James Fell 1814.jpg|thumb|An example of an English \u00a31 banknote (1814) (Gloucester Old Bank note for Charles Evans & James Fell)]]\nOn 13 September 1820 Callaghan was tried for \"felonious disposal of and putting away a [[Forgery|forged]] and counterfeit bank note for \u00a31 with intent to defraud the [[Bank of England]]\" at the Middlesex Gaol Delivery ([[Old Bailey]]), London, England. She was sentenced to 14 years (death commuted) and was transported to New South Wales, arriving on 18 December 1821.<ref name=\"founder\"/>\n\nOn 27 March 1822, she committed an offence of being drunk and disorderly and was in HM Gaol for one week. She had to wear an [[iron collar]] for the period and to sit in [[stocks]] twice, two hours at each time.<ref name=\"founder\"/>  She committed another offence on June 25 when she was caught sneaking out of her master\u2019s premises on the 24th and remained absent all night. She was sentenced to sit in stocks for three hours that day.<ref name=\"founder\"/> In 1823, Callaghan committed an offence when she was absent from her master\u2019s premises one day and night. She was punished for a week, with bread and water rations and had to sit in the stocks for two hours each day.<ref name=\"founder\"/>\n\n== Family ==\n[[File:John batman.jpg|left|Callaghan's husband John Batman]]\n\nCallaghan married [[John Batman]] on 29 March 1828 in St John's, Launceston, Tasmania.<ref name=Manuscript>{{Citation | title=Memorial manuscript containing the petition of John Batman to Colonel George Arthur for leave to marry convict Eliza Thompson (alias Elizabeth Callaghan), 1828 | publication-date=1828 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/173688030 | accessdate=10 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe couple had seven daughters and a son.  Their only son, John Charles Batman, died aged just 8 or 9 years old by drowning in the [[Yarra River]] on 11 January 1845.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article228064094 |title=Domestic Intelligence. |newspaper=The Melbourne Weekly Courier |volume=II |issue=55 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=17 January 1845 |accessdate=3 June 2019 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBatman became ill around 1835, and in February 1839 Elizabeth sailed to England. He died on 6 May 1839 but she only heard of this when she returned to Australia in March 1840. His will left her only \u00a35, which she and her second husband challenged in a lengthy but unsuccessful lawsuit.<ref name=Brown />\n\nAfter Batman died, Callaghan married William Willoughby, her former husband's clerk in 1841.<ref name=\"founder\" />  In July 1853 her daughter, Elizabeth Mary, described her late mother as \"Elizabeth Callan, governess\".<ref name=Brown/>\n\n== Death and legacy ==\nCallaghan was murdered in 1852 in [[Geelong]], being beaten and kicked to death in a bar-room brawl.<ref name=EF>{{cite book|editor1-last=E.F.|title=Callaghan and Batman, Van Dieman's Land, 1825|date=1978|publisher=Sullivan's Cove|location=Adelaide|isbn=0909442061|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/version/11711886}}</ref> At this time she was known as Sara Willoughby and had been described as \"of somewhat abandoned character\".<ref name=Brown />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Convicts in Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Callaghan, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1852 deaths]]\n[[Category:Convicts transported to Australia]]\n[[Category:18th-century Australian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Callaghan''' (1802-1852; also '''Eliza Thompson''',<ref name=Brown /> later '''Elizabeth Batman''' and '''Sarah Willoughby''') was a [[Convicts in Australia|convict]] born in [[Ireland]] in 1802 and shipped to the penal colony in [[New South Wales]] at the age of 17 for passing a [[counterfeit]] bank note for [[Banknotes of the pound sterling|\u00a3]]1 with intent to [[defraud]] the [[Bank of England]].<ref name=\"poi-australia.com.au\">{{cite web|url = http://poi-australia.com.au/eliza-batman-nee-callaghan/|title = Eliza Batman (n\u00e9e Callaghan)|work = POI Australia|accessdate = 16 November 2015}}</ref> She travelled with 103 other convicts on 6 June 1821 and arrived in [[Hobart]] on 7 January 1822.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Convict Records: Elizabeth Callaghan|url = http://www.convictrecords.com.au/convicts/callaghan/elizabeth/93261|website = www.convictrecords.com.au|accessdate = 2015-11-17}}</ref><ref name=Brown>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=P.L.|title=Batman, John (1801\u20131839)|date=1966|publisher=Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|location=Melbourne|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/batman-john-1752/text1947|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> The town of [[Mount Eliza, Victoria|Mount Eliza]] near [[Melbourne]] is named after her.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n== Early life ==\nCallaghan had roots in [[Ennis]], [[County Clare]], Ireland. She worked as a servant.<ref name=\"founder\">{{cite web|url=http://www.founders-storylines.com/mugsheets/convicts/profile/1126/elizabeth_callaghan|title=Elizabeth CALLAGHAN|work=founders-storylines.com|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> It has been said that her family of origin were land owners and her grandfather of exceptional wealth. There appears to be some separation of Elizabeth\u2019s father from her grandparents and suggestions that her father was a very unhappy man. Her mother was an elegant, learned and strong lady of exceptional [[character structure|character]]. The family struggled, and Callaghan was sent on her way at just seventeen.  Beautiful, elegant, fiery and learned \u2013 her mother was confident that she would easily find her place in the world.<ref name=\"poi-australia.com.au\"/>\n\n== Criminal record ==\n[[File:\u00a31 Gloucester Old Bank note for Charles Evans & James Fell 1814.jpg|thumb|An example of an English \u00a31 banknote (1814) (Gloucester Old Bank note for Charles Evans & James Fell)]]\nOn 13 September 1820 Callaghan was tried for \"felonious disposal of and putting away a [[Forgery|forged]] and counterfeit bank note for \u00a31 with intent to defraud the [[Bank of England]]\" at the Middlesex Gaol Delivery ([[Old Bailey]]), London, England. She was sentenced to 14 years (death commuted) and was transported to New South Wales, arriving on 18 December 1821.<ref name=\"founder\"/>\n\nOn 27 March 1822, she committed an offence of being drunk and disorderly and was in HM Gaol for one week. She had to wear an [[iron collar]] for the period and to sit in [[stocks]] twice, two hours at each time.<ref name=\"founder\"/>  She committed another offence on June 25 when she was caught sneaking out of her master\u2019s premises on the 24th and remained absent all night. She was sentenced to sit in stocks for three hours that day.<ref name=\"founder\"/> In 1823, Callaghan committed an offence when she was absent from her master\u2019s premises one day and night. She was punished for a week, with bread and water rations and had to sit in the stocks for two hours each day.<ref name=\"founder\"/>\n\n== Family ==\n[[File:John batman.jpg|left|Callaghan's husband John Batman]]\n\nCallaghan married [[John Batman]] on 29 March 1828 in St John's, Launceston, Tasmania.<ref name=Manuscript>{{Citation | title=Memorial manuscript containing the petition of John Batman to Colonel George Arthur for leave to marry convict Eliza Thompson (alias Elizabeth Callaghan), 1828 | publication-date=1828 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/173688030 | accessdate=10 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe couple had seven daughters and a son.  Their only son, John Charles Batman, died aged just 8 or 9 years old by drowning in the [[Yarra River]] on 11 January 1845.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article228064094 |title=Domestic Intelligence. |newspaper=The Melbourne Weekly Courier |volume=II |issue=55 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=17 January 1845 |accessdate=3 June 2019 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBatman became ill around 1835, and in February 1839 Elizabeth sailed to England. He died on 6 May 1839 but she only heard of this when she returned to Australia in March 1840. His will left her only \u00a35, which she and her second husband challenged in a lengthy but unsuccessful lawsuit.<ref name=Brown />\n\nAfter Batman died, Callaghan married William Willoughby, her former husband's clerk in 1841.<ref name=\"founder\" />  In July 1853 her daughter, Elizabeth Mary, described her late mother as \"Elizabeth Callan, governess\".<ref name=Brown/>\n\n== Death and legacy ==\nCallaghan was murdered in 1852 in [[Geelong]], being beaten and kicked to death in a bar-room brawl.<ref name=EF>{{cite book|editor1-last=E.F.|title=Callaghan and Batman, Van Dieman's Land, 1825|date=1978|publisher=Sullivan's Cove|location=Adelaide|isbn=0909442061|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/version/11711886}}</ref> At this time she was known as Sara Willoughby and had been described as \"of somewhat abandoned character\".<ref name=Brown />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Convicts in Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Callaghan, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:Australian convict women]]\n[[Category:1852 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Chris.sherlock", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_Callaghan"}
{"title_page": "2019 California power shutoffs", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title           = <!-- Title to display, if other than page name -->\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| image_alt       = \n| caption         = \n| time            = \n| duration        = 23 days (original)\n| date            = *{{Start and end dates|2019|10|9|2019|11|1|mf=yes}}<!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{start and end dates|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --><ref>https://abc7news.com/society/pg-e-says-essentially-all-customers-restored-after-outages/5661736/</ref>\n*{{Start date|2019|11|20}}<ref name=\"LA Times November\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-11-20/pge-shutting-off-power-to-450-000-people-in-norther|title=PG&E shutting off power to 450,000 people in Northern California|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=November 20, 2019|first=Alejandra|last=Reyes-Velarde|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n| venue           = \n| location        = [[California]]\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|region:XXXX_type:event|display=inline,title}} -->\n| also_known_as   = \n| type            = [[Power outage|Power shutoff]]\n| cause           = Wildfire risk due to strong winds\n| reported deaths = 1{{r|Fox death}}\n}}\nThe '''2019 California power shutoffs''', known as public safety power shutoff (PSPS) events, were massive preemptive <!-- it was not \"planned\" in any ordinary sense of that word. PG&E preemptively shut off power due to perceived risk of wildfires starting in high winds due to high-voltage power lines. Same with the San Diego utility: preemptive shutoff --> [[Power outage|power shutoffs]] that occurred in approximately 30 counties in [[Northern California]] and several areas in [[Southern California]] from October 9 to November 1, 2019, by [[Pacific Gas and Electric Company]] (PG&E), [[Southern California Edison]] (SCE), and [[San Diego Gas & Electric]] (SDG&E). The power shutoffs were an attempt to prevent wildfires from being started by electrical equipment during strong and dry winds. The shutoffs initially affected around 800,000 customers, or about 2.5 million people<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuller |first1=Thomas |title=Fearing Wildfires, PG&E Cuts Power to 500,000 in California |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/09/us/pge-shut-off-power-outage.html |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |ref=1}}</ref><ref name=\"morris\">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=J.D |last2=Cabanatuan |first2= Michael |title=PG&E: Massive power shut-off to hit 800,000 customers, could extend nearly a week |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/california-wildfires/article/PG-E-power-shut-off-257-000-Bay-Area-residents-14500945.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|date=October 9, 2019|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/wildfires-california-fires-rage-as-residents-scramble-without-power-pge/|title=Wildfires rage in California as residents scramble without power|date=October 10, 2019|work=CBS News|language=en|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>{{update after|2019|10|28}} but expanded to cause over 3 million people to lose utility-provided electrical power by late October as more  [[public utility|utility companies]] from around the state also did preemptive power shutoffs.\n\nThe shutdowns have drawn widespread fierce backlash and criticism from residents as well as government officials as PG&E, SCE, SDG&E and the [[California Public Utilities Commission]] issued an apology.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}<!-- source for the apology?  did they apologize for the shutoffs as in \"we made a mistake and flipped the wrong switch?  or more of a \"we're sorry we have to do this but we don't want to start fires with our high-energy electric lines? --> Many residents complained of either being misinformed or not informed when shutdowns would occur, while officials such as California governor [[Gavin Newsom]] blamed the shutdowns on PG&E's \"greed and mismanagement.\"<ref name=\"No recourse\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/there-is-no-recourse-blackouts-draw-ire-across-northern-california/2019/10/10/6d514e66-eba6-11e9-9306-47cb0324fd44_story.html|title=\u2018There is no recourse\u2019: Blackouts draw ire across Northern California|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|first=Scott|last=Wilson|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref> Some people expressed their frustrations through vandalism and violence, including the egging of a PG&E office's front doors and someone shooting at a PG&E vehicle.<ref name=\"Vandalism\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/california-power-outage-frustrations-pge-office-vandalized-truck-shot|title=California power outage frustrations boil over as PG&E office vandalized, truck shot at on Interstate 5|publisher=[[FOX News]]|first=Travis|last=Fedschun|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor the state's largest utility, PG&E, to bury all of its [[Electric power distribution|distribution lines]] (relatively low voltage lines which bring power to homes, not the higher voltage [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] lines) would cost {{USD|15,000}} per customer.<ref name=\"USN_1\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n{{expand section|date=October 2019}}\nThe \u201cPublic Safety Power Shutoff\u201d (PSPS) has been standard practice in California for many years, though in the past, the preemptive shutoffs occurred predominantly in rural areas. PG&E warned the state for months of its impending action, set to commence when the combination of high autumn winds and dry conditions made the fires more likely to happen.<ref name=\"CJ 2019-10-11\">{{cite news |last1=Meigs |first1=James |title=California Goes Dark. Multiple factors have led to planned electricity blackouts across the Golden State. |url=https://www.city-journal.org/planned-electricity-blackouts-california? |work=City Journal |publisher=Manhattan Institute for Policy Research |date=October 11, 2019 |location=New York NY}}</ref> PG&E began its series of power blackouts in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] on Wednesday, October 9, at around 12 AM PDT in order to reduce the risks of devastating wildfires caused by PG&E's power lines or equipment, like the [[October 2017 Northern California wildfires]] and the [[2018 Camp Fire]], responsible for a combined total of 95 deaths.<ref name=\"morris\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Julie |title=Cal Fire: PG&E equipment caused 12 Northern California fires during October firestorm |url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/8413929-181/cal-fire-pge-equipment-caused |work=Santa Rosa Press Democrat |publisher=Sonoma Media Investments |date=June 18, 2018 |location=Santa Rosa CA}}</ref> \n\nAs California's population has continued to grow in suburban and exurban areas that were formerly wilderness, the risk and size of fires has escalated. More than a third of California's housing is now located in areas known as [[wildland\u2013urban interface]].{{r|CJ 2019-10-11}} When wildfires happen upon these communities, they become more dangerous and leap from structure to structure in what is called \u201cfast-moving urban conflagrations\u201d that firefighters find difficult to stop.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martinuzzi |first1=Sebastian |title=The 2010 Wildland-Urban Interface of the Conterminous United States |url=https://www.fs.fed.us/nrs/pubs/rmap/rmap_nrs8.pdf |website=US Forest Service |publisher=US Department of Agriculture |location=Baltimore MD}}</ref>\n\n== Legal setting ==\nBesides safety, one of the reasons behind PG&E's (now moving into bankruptcy) imposition of the blackouts is a legal doctrine known as [[inverse condemnation]], which makes California utilities responsible for wildfire destruction regardless of whether the utility acted negligently or not. California's interpretation of inverse condemnation is unique. The tenet is applied in other states, usually to government entities that damage private property when engaged in a public service. California's courts have ruled the principle can be applied to utilities. So the utilities are held liable for damage, even if they comply with all of California's strict energy-related rules.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baker |first1=David |title=The California Rule That Doomed PG&E: Inverse Condemnation |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-15/the-california-rule-that-doomed-pg-e-inverse-condemnation |website=Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg LP |location=New York NY |date=January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis policy resulted in $30B of liability for PG&E from the 2017 & 2018 fires and drove it to bankruptcy proceedings.{{ r | LAT_1 | p=1 | q=PG&E filed for bankruptcy protection in January in anticipation of massive legal fees resulting from wildfires linked to its electrical equipment in recent years. State law requires utilities to pay for such fires, regardless of whether a company&apos;s negligence may have caused the blaze. }}\n{{ r | LAT_2 | p=1 | q=Under state guidelines, a utility or its customers are responsible for paying property damages from wildfires linked to the company&apos;s equipment. With aging infrastructure electrifying remote areas of increasingly hot and dry terrain, the cost and risk have grown significantly in recent years. Pacific Gas & Electric filed for bankruptcy, anticipating some $30 billion in liability for fires in 2017 and 2018, earlier this year. }}\nIn July 2019, a new $21 billion wildfire trust fund was created to pay for damages from future wildfires, started with a 50-50 balance of utility and customer monies and also reduced the liability threshold for utilities to where customers must prove negilgence before companies are held liable.{{ r | LAT_2 | p=1 | q=California&apos;s investor-owned utility companies have agreed to open up their wallets to pay into the state&apos;s wildfire fund in exchange for less financial responsibility when blazes are linked to their equipment. ... The fund, propped up by $21 billion split equally between utility customers and shareholders, is meant to act as a second insurance policy for publicly traded electricity companies and to offset concerns from Wall Street about massive monetary liabilities that have threatened to upend the energy market in California. ... The law takes $10.5 billion from electricity customers through the continuation of a charge on monthly bills that was set to expire next year. In return, wildfire costs that would typically lead to higher bills for customers will instead be paid out by the fund, potentially avoiding price hikes. ... For their $10.5 billion, the utilities are allowed to tap into the fund to pay wildfire damages that exceed insurance coverage. The law also shifts the burden of proof in regulatory proceedings \u2014 another benefit for the utilities \u2014 and requires outside groups to intervene to prove that the company failed to properly manage its system to prevent the fire. }}\n\nCritics of inverse condemnation point out that it can lead to utility bankruptcies which can threaten the integrity of the California power grid as well as hurt financing the states' efforts for renewable energy and against climate change, one of the causes of the intensified fire threat.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bradford |first1=Peter |title=Making PG&E pay more than its fair share of fire damage could backfire on the state |url=https://www.sacbee.com/opinion/california-forum/article212316269.html |work=Sacramento Bee |publisher=McClatchy Company |date=May 31, 2018 |location=Sacramento CA}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to court cases in recent years and the evolution of [[case law]] which have made new standards of legal liability, the [[Government of California|California State]] [[California State Legislature|legislature]] and the [[Governor of California|Governor]]<!-- it take both legislature and governor to enact a law; so action on both sides of the government of california here --> also enacted new [[statutory law]]s to modify the legal regime under which electrical utilities operate in California.  Over 20 new wildfire-related laws were enacted in the 2019 legislative session, several of them affecting the electrical service providing utility companies.<ref name=lat20191002>[https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-02/california-power-shutoffs-new-laws-newsom California adds new rules for planned power shutoffs under laws signed by Newsom], Los Angeles Times, October 2, 2019, accessed October 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Undergrounding==\nThe fire risk from the electricity supply is principally from the large amount of energy carried in [[Overhead power line|above-ground]] power lines, which under fault conditions can become a factor in the [[Fire triangle|ignition]] of wildfires. [[Public utility|Public utilities]] in the state of California have a total of {{convert|26,000| miles}} of high voltage [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] lines, and {{convert|240,000 |miles}} of  [[Electric power distribution|distribution]] lines.  Distribution lines bring electricity directly to homes; two thirds of them statewide are above ground.{{ r | USN_1| p=1 | q=California has 25,526 miles of higher voltage transmission lines, and 239,557 miles of distribution lines, two-thirds of which are overhead, according to CPUC. }}\nFor transmission lines, the cost of constructing these underground is approximately {{USD|80 million}} per mile{{ r | SFC_1 | p=1 | q=Those transmission lines, typically supported by tall, steel-lattice towers, carry electricity at high voltages across long distances. They are far more expensive to place in the ground than the lower-voltage distribution lines that bring electricity directly into residential neighborhoods. \u201cIt makes undergrounding distribution look cheap \u2014 think like $80 million a mile,\u201d Wara said. \u201cYou basically dig a trench and build a building around the transmission line.\u201d PG&E has more than 18,000 miles of transmission lines. }}\nwhile for distribution lines, the construction cost of new underground lines is about {{USD|3 million}} per mile, compared to overhead lines at about $800,000 per mile.{{ r | USN_1| p=1 | q=It costs about $3 million per mile to convert underground electric distribution lines from overhead, while the cost to build a mile of new overhead line is less than a third of that, at approximately $800,000 per mile,... }}\n\nThe state's largest utility, PG&E, has {{convert|107,000 |miles}} of distribution lines, {{convert|81,000 |miles}} of which are overhead.  The cost to convert all of PG&E's overhead distribution lines to underground lines would be approximately {{USD|240 billion}}, or roughly {{USD|15,000}} per PG&E customer. (This cost estimate is only for distribution lines, not the higher voltage transmission lines.){{ r | USN_1| p=1 | q=PG&E, the state&apos;s largest utility, maintains approximately 81,000 miles of overhead distribution lines and approximately 26,000 miles of underground distribution lines. It also has about 18,000 miles of larger transmission lines, the majority of which are overhead lines. At a cost of $3 million per mile, undergrounding 81,000 miles of distribution lines would cost $243 billion. PG&E has 16 million customers; distributing that expense equally would amount to a bill of more than $15,000 per account. }}\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2019}}\n*Several hundred miles to the south of San Francisco, [[San Diego Gas & Electric]] shut off power to approximately 400 customers in eastern [[San Diego County]], California on Friday, October 4, 2019, due to combustion hazards posed by the first [[Santa Ana wind]] event of the fall. {{As of|2019|10|8|df=US}}, SDG&E anticipated restoring power by the following Friday, October 11.<ref name=\"cbs20191008\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs8.com/article/news/local/sdge-warns-of-potential-power-shut-off-across-san-diego-county/509-2a630c51-5c18-40d1-b9ee-b703379f7864|title=SDG&E shuts off power to some East San Diego County residents|website=KFMB|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>{{update after|2019|10|21}}\n*On Wednesday, October 9, around 12 AM PDT, PG&E began to shut off power to many regions, as a pre-emptive measure to help avoid wildfires caused by electric lines.<ref name=\"morris\"/> The shutdown of nearly {{convert|25000|mi|km}} of electric lines was expected to affect more than 2 million people, of PG&E's 16 million total served.  Power was projected to remain off for up to several days after the high winds subside as all of the shutdown lines must be inspected for wind damage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/victim-own-failure-why-pg-235612401.html|title='A victim of their own failure': Why PG&E's massive power shutdown in California was inevitable|website=news.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n*On October 10, SCE cut power to 13,000 customers, (and warned 175,000 of potential power cuts depending on conditions).<ref name=OCR_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.ocregister.com/2019/10/09/map-sce-says-power-outages-could-come-to-these-southern-california-areas/ | title= Map: Where Southern California Edison has cut power or is considering it | last=Johnson | first=Nikie | newspaper=[[Orange County Register]] | date=October 10, 2019 | access-date=October 27, 2019 | archive-url= | archive-date= | url-status=live | pages= | quote=Southern California Edison has shut off power to about 12,900 customers Thursday, Oct. 10, while an area containing almost 174,000 SCE customers is under consideration for power shutoffs as a way to prevent wildfires from starting. }}</ref>\n*By October 11, three days into the pre-emptive blackout, winds had begun to subside and PG&E restored power to some customers, but about 500,000 out of a total of approximately 800,000 still had power cut off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-10/unprecedented-california-blackout-spreads-with-millions-in-dark|title=Unprecedented California Blackout Ending as PG&E Restores Power\n|first=Mark|last=Chediak|date=October 10, 2019|website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref>{{update after|2019|10|20}}<!-- it's October 20 now; is the power shutoff still in force for some???  If it is over, when was it?  And power was restored under what sort of protocol? who got power first?  etc. -->\n\n*On October 22, PG&E was warning of a potential second round of preemptive shutoffs which could affect over 500,000 customers.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/california-pg-e-warns-fresh-145431402.html California: PG&E warns of fresh power shutoffs for 500,000 due to fire weather], October 22, 2019.</ref><!--  -->\n*On October 25, San Diego Gas & Electric had cut power to 19,000 households, potentially rising up to 50,000, in San Diego County because of a combination of high winds, high temperature, and dry conditions.<ref name=MSN_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/weather/topstories/sdg-26e-shutoffs-nearly-19000-without-power-in-san-diego-county/ar-AAJnbu1 | title=SDG&E Shutoffs: Nearly 19,000 Without Power In San Diego County | last= | first= | newspaper=[[MSN]] | date= | access-date=October 27, 2019 | archive-url= | archive-date= | url-status=live | quote=The predicted Santa Ana winds initially prompted San Diego Gas & Electric to notify roughly 24,000 customers of potential power shutoffs for safety reasons, but as of 7 a.m. Friday that number had increased to just over 47,500. }}</ref>\n*On October 26, PG&E announced that it would be shutting off power for 940,000 customers in Northern California, again with the rationale of preventing more wildfires.  This \"is the second major shutoff by PG&E this month.\"<ref name=cnbc20191026>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/26/pge-will-shut-off-power-to-940000-customers-in-northern-california-to-reduce-wildfire-risk.html PG&E will cut power to 940,000 as California wildfires rage: \u2018Most serious weather situation in recent memory\u2019], CNBC, October 26, 2019.</ref>\n*On October 27, over 1 million customers and a total of over 3,000,000 individuals were affected. A total of more than 3 million people across California were without power that day.<ref name=\"Historic Blackout Underway\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/california-wildfires/article/PG-E-outages-Over-3-million-people-blacked-out-14566085.php|title=PG&E outages: Historic blackout underway, 1.3 million in Bay Area without power|first=J. D.|last=Morris|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=October 27, 2019|accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*By October 28, [[Southern California Edison]] had shut off power to 25,000 customers and conducted notifications for up to 350,000 more in 10 counties around the greater Los Angeles area.<ref name=ladn20191028>[https://www.dailynews.com/2019/10/28/power-outage-map-where-southern-california-edison-has-cut-electricity-or-is-considering/ Power outage map: Where Southern California Edison has cut electricity or is considering it], Los Angeles Daily News, October 28, 2019, accessed October 29, 2019.</ref>\n*On November 20, PG&E shut off power to approximately 450,000 individuals in Northern California.<ref name=\"LA Times November\" />\n\n==Impacts==\nA man dependent on an oxygen supply died 12 minutes after the outage started in his area on October 11. An investigation has been initiated.  His family said he could not reach his battery-powered tank in time.{{r|Fox death}} Large numbers of other disabled people reported issues with poor communication by PG&E of when shutoffs would occur, and with the inability to power or charge electrical devices on which their wellbeing depended during shutoffs. Affected devices included ventilators, oxygen concentrators, nebulizers, dialysis machines, refrigerators for drugs such as insulin, and electrically powered beds, hoists and wheelchairs. PG&E had a list of over 30,000 customers registered on their Medical Baseline program as being vulnerable to shutoffs, but used it only as a contact list, leaving the affected disabled customers unsupported. Dependence on the Medical Baseline list meant PG&E inevitably missing many more disabled people not registered with the program. Others who were registered reported they were not contacted. PG&E also refused to give many local counties access to the Medical Baseline list, leaving them unable to check on vulnerable residents. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/11/california-pge-utility-power-shutoff-disabled</ref> <ref>http://www.capradio.org/articles/2019/12/02/pge-withheld-information-about-medically-at-risk-customers-ahead-of-major-power-shutoff/</ref>\n\nUnder [[backup power]] on October 11, 2019 [UTC], the Mission Operations Center (MOC) at the [[Space Sciences Laboratory]] at [[University of California, Berkeley]] oversaw the deployment of a [[Ionospheric Connection Explorer|satellite]] launched from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]]. Paula Milano, who helps run the Laboratory, did not want to postpone the launch saying \u201cIf a scrub of the mission happens because of Berkeley, that's a huge black eye for us, and it's a huge public black eye for [[NASA]].\u201d After notification on October 7, the lab began extensive preparation for the power outage.{{r|Wired}}\n\nBy late October, water had been restricted for some{{clarify|extent? how many affected? by what water-providing agencies?  or companies?|date=November 2019}} in areas which rely on pump stations.<ref name=\"Mercury News\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/10/29/power-shutdown-do-you-have-to-pay-pge-plus-other-questions-answered/|title=Power shutdown: Do you have to pay PG&E, plus other questions answered|first=Levi|last=Sumagaysay|date=October 29, 2019|accessdate=October 29, 2019|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref>{{update after|2019|11|6|df=US}}<!-- and then what?  was it restricted for a few days?  weeks?  has it been restored? -->\n\n[[Sonoma\u2013Marin Area Rail Transit]] [[commuter rail]] services were cancelled on October 28<ref>{{cite web |title=Service Advisory: All Trains Canceled for Monday, October 28 |url=http://www.sonomamarintrain.org/node/333 |publisher=SMART |accessdate=October 30, 2019}}</ref> and 29<ref>{{cite web |title=Service Advisory: All Trains Canceled for Tuesday, October 30 |url=http://www.sonomamarintrain.org/node/334 |publisher=SMART |accessdate=October 30, 2019}}</ref> due to loss of power at [[Level crossing|crossings]] throughout the system. Partial service as far north as Downtown [[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]] was restored the following day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Smart Train Service Running On Limited Schedule Wednesday Through Nov. 6. |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/bayarea/article/Smart-Train-Service-Running-On-Limited-Schedule-14572872.php |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |agency=Bay City News Service |publisher=SFGate |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Potential fires averted==\n\nAfter the early October power shutoffs, the CEO of PG&E stated that they found more than 100 cases of \"wind-related damage\" to the 25,000 miles of power lines they had de-energized. {{ r | SFC_PGE_statement }} He also stated \"More than half of PG&E\u2019s 70,000-square-mile service area in Northern and Central California is considered by state officials to be at high risk of wildfire.  In 2012, that designation applied to just 15% of our service area.\" {{ r | SFC_PGE_statement }}\n\nBy the end of October, PG&E officials told a federal judge that the power shutoffs so far helped prevent up to 56 wildfires. This was mostly caused by problems in previous inspections of power lines.<ref>{{cite news |title=PG&E Says 56 Fires Could Have Been Sparked Without Mass Shutoffs This Month |url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/pge-says-56-fires-could-have-been-sparked-without-mass-shutoffs-this-month/2054726/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |agency=NBC Bay Area |date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019 California wildfires]]\n* [[List of California wildfires]]\n* [[List of major power outages]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Wired\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/icon-launch-blackout/|title=UC Berkeley Was About to Launch a Satellite. Then PG&E Said It Was Cutting Power|work=Wired|first=Matt |last=Simon|date=October 17, 2019|access-date=October 19, 2019|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=LAT_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-wildfire-liability-law-gavin-newsom-legislature-20190529-story.html | title=Newsom and legislative leaders decline to embrace changes to California\u2019s wildfire liability law | last=Luna | first=Taryn | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=May 29, 2019 | access-date=October 16, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602055944/https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-wildfire-liability-law-gavin-newsom-legislature-20190529-story.html | archive-date=June 2, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=LAT_2 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-25/california-utilities-agree-to-pay-10-5-billion-into-new-wildfire-fund| title=California utilities agree to pay $10.5 billion into new wildfire fund  | last=Luna | first=Taryn | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | | date=July 25, 2019 | access-date=October 16, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801003122/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-25/california-utilities-agree-to-pay-10-5-billion-into-new-wildfire-fund | archive-date=August 1, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=USN_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/10/11/bury-california-power-lines-wildfire-blackout-fix-unlikely-work/3946935002/ | title=California power lines spark wildfires and prompt blackouts. Why not just bury them? | last=Wilson | first=Janet | newspaper=[[USA Today]] | date=October 11, 2019 | access-date=October 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015030035/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/10/11/bury-california-power-lines-wildfire-blackout-fix-unlikely-work/3946935002/ | archive-date=October 15, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SFC_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/california-wildfires/article/Put-PG-E-s-power-lines-underground-It-can-be-14565060.php | title=Put PG&E\u2019s power lines underground? It can be done \u2014 expensively and slowly | last=Morris | first=J.D. | newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date= October 27, 2019| access-date=October 27, 2019 | archive-url= | archive-date= | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Fox death\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/oxygen-dependent-man-dies-12-minutes-after-pge-cuts-power-to-his-home|title=Oxygen-dependent California man dies 12 minutes after PG&E cuts power to his home|last=Phillips|first=Morgan|date=October 11, 2019|work=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SFC_PGE_statement > {{ cite news | url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/PG-E-CEO-We-hear-the-anger-are-working-hard-to-14540181.php | title=PG&E CEO: We hear the anger, are working hard to avoid power shut-offs | last=Johnson | first=Bill | newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=October 17, 2019 | access-date=November 19, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022181129/https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/PG-E-CEO-We-hear-the-anger-are-working-hard-to-14540181.php | archive-date=October 22, 2019 | url-status=live | quote=We did see damage to our system because of the wind. When we patrolled all 25,000 miles of lines that we turned off, we found more than 100 confirmed cases of wind-related damage \u2014 including trees into power lines and downed power lines. Had we not shut off power, this type of damage could have sparked a fire. In fact, vegetation contacting lines was the very cause of a number of fires in the North Bay two years ago. }} </ref>\n\n}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in California]]\n[[Category:October 2019 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Pacific Gas and Electric Company]]\n[[Category:Power outages in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title           = <!-- Title to display, if other than page name -->\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| image_alt       = \n| caption         = \n| time            = \n| duration        = 23 days (original)\n| date            = *{{Start and end dates|2019|10|9|2019|11|1|mf=yes}}<!-- {{start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{start and end dates|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --><ref>https://abc7news.com/society/pg-e-says-essentially-all-customers-restored-after-outages/5661736/</ref>\n*{{Start date|df=yes|2019|11|20}}<ref name=\"LA Times November\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-11-20/pge-shutting-off-power-to-450-000-people-in-norther|title=PG&E shutting off power to 450,000 people in Northern California|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=November 20, 2019|first=Alejandra|last=Reyes-Velarde|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n| venue           = \n| location        = [[California]]\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|region:XXXX_type:event|display=inline,title}} -->\n| also_known_as   = \n| type            = [[Power outage|Power shutoff]]\n| cause           = Wildfire risk due to strong winds\n| reported deaths = 1{{r|Fox death}}\n}}\nThe '''2019 California power shutoffs''', known as public safety power shutoff (PSPS) events, were massive preemptive <!-- it was not \"planned\" in any ordinary sense of that word. PG&E preemptively shut off power due to perceived risk of wildfires starting in high winds due to high-voltage power lines. Same with the San Diego utility: preemptive shutoff --> [[Power outage|power shutoffs]] that occurred in approximately 30 counties in [[Northern California]] and several areas in [[Southern California]] from October 9 to November 1, 2019, by [[Pacific Gas and Electric Company]] (PG&E), [[Southern California Edison]] (SCE), and [[San Diego Gas & Electric]] (SDG&E). The power shutoffs were an attempt to prevent wildfires from being started by electrical equipment during strong and dry winds. The shutoffs initially affected around 800,000 customers, or about 2.5 million people<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuller |first1=Thomas |title=Fearing Wildfires, PG&E Cuts Power to 500,000 in California |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/09/us/pge-shut-off-power-outage.html |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |ref=1}}</ref><ref name=\"morris\">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=J.D |last2=Cabanatuan |first2= Michael |title=PG&E: Massive power shut-off to hit 800,000 customers, could extend nearly a week |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/california-wildfires/article/PG-E-power-shut-off-257-000-Bay-Area-residents-14500945.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|date=October 9, 2019|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/wildfires-california-fires-rage-as-residents-scramble-without-power-pge/|title=Wildfires rage in California as residents scramble without power|date=October 10, 2019|work=CBS News|language=en|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>{{update after|2019|10|28}} but expanded to cause over 3 million people to lose utility-provided electrical power by late October as more  [[public utility|utility companies]] from around the state also did preemptive power shutoffs.\n\nThe shutdowns have drawn widespread fierce backlash and criticism from residents as well as government officials as PG&E, SCE, SDG&E and the [[California Public Utilities Commission]] issued an apology.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}<!-- source for the apology?  did they apologize for the shutoffs as in \"we made a mistake and flipped the wrong switch?  or more of a \"we're sorry we have to do this but we don't want to start fires with our high-energy electric lines? --> Many residents complained of either being misinformed or not informed when shutdowns would occur, while officials such as California governor [[Gavin Newsom]] blamed the shutdowns on PG&E's \"greed and mismanagement.\"<ref name=\"No recourse\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/there-is-no-recourse-blackouts-draw-ire-across-northern-california/2019/10/10/6d514e66-eba6-11e9-9306-47cb0324fd44_story.html|title=\u2018There is no recourse\u2019: Blackouts draw ire across Northern California|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|first=Scott|last=Wilson|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref> Some people expressed their frustrations through vandalism and violence, including the egging of a PG&E office's front doors and someone shooting at a PG&E vehicle.<ref name=\"Vandalism\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/california-power-outage-frustrations-pge-office-vandalized-truck-shot|title=California power outage frustrations boil over as PG&E office vandalized, truck shot at on Interstate 5|publisher=[[FOX News]]|first=Travis|last=Fedschun|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor the state's largest utility, PG&E, to bury all of its [[Electric power distribution|distribution lines]] (relatively low voltage lines which bring power to homes, not the higher voltage [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] lines) would cost {{USD|15,000}} per customer.<ref name=\"USN_1\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n{{expand section|date=October 2019}}\nThe \u201cPublic Safety Power Shutoff\u201d (PSPS) has been standard practice in California for many years, though in the past, the preemptive shutoffs occurred predominantly in rural areas. PG&E warned the state for months of its impending action, set to commence when the combination of high autumn winds and dry conditions made the fires more likely to happen.<ref name=\"CJ 2019-10-11\">{{cite news |last1=Meigs |first1=James |title=California Goes Dark. Multiple factors have led to planned electricity blackouts across the Golden State. |url=https://www.city-journal.org/planned-electricity-blackouts-california? |work=City Journal |publisher=Manhattan Institute for Policy Research |date=October 11, 2019 |location=New York NY}}</ref> PG&E began its series of power blackouts in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] on Wednesday, October 9, at around 12 AM PDT in order to reduce the risks of devastating wildfires caused by PG&E's power lines or equipment, like the [[October 2017 Northern California wildfires]] and the [[2018 Camp Fire]], responsible for a combined total of 95 deaths.<ref name=\"morris\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Julie |title=Cal Fire: PG&E equipment caused 12 Northern California fires during October firestorm |url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/8413929-181/cal-fire-pge-equipment-caused |work=Santa Rosa Press Democrat |publisher=Sonoma Media Investments |date=June 18, 2018 |location=Santa Rosa CA}}</ref> \n\nAs California's population has continued to grow in suburban and exurban areas that were formerly wilderness, the risk and size of fires has escalated. More than a third of California's housing is now located in areas known as [[wildland\u2013urban interface]].{{r|CJ 2019-10-11}} When wildfires happen upon these communities, they become more dangerous and leap from structure to structure in what is called \u201cfast-moving urban conflagrations\u201d that firefighters find difficult to stop.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martinuzzi |first1=Sebastian |title=The 2010 Wildland-Urban Interface of the Conterminous United States |url=https://www.fs.fed.us/nrs/pubs/rmap/rmap_nrs8.pdf |website=US Forest Service |publisher=US Department of Agriculture |location=Baltimore MD}}</ref>\n\n== Legal setting ==\nBesides safety, one of the reasons behind PG&E's (now moving into bankruptcy) imposition of the blackouts is a legal doctrine known as [[inverse condemnation]], which makes California utilities responsible for wildfire destruction regardless of whether the utility acted negligently or not. California's interpretation of inverse condemnation is unique. The tenet is applied in other states, usually to government entities that damage private property when engaged in a public service. California's courts have ruled the principle can be applied to utilities. So the utilities are held liable for damage, even if they comply with all of California's strict energy-related rules.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baker |first1=David |title=The California Rule That Doomed PG&E: Inverse Condemnation |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-15/the-california-rule-that-doomed-pg-e-inverse-condemnation |website=Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg LP |location=New York NY |date=January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis policy resulted in $30B of liability for PG&E from the 2017 & 2018 fires and drove it to bankruptcy proceedings.{{ r | LAT_1 | p=1 | q=PG&E filed for bankruptcy protection in January in anticipation of massive legal fees resulting from wildfires linked to its electrical equipment in recent years. State law requires utilities to pay for such fires, regardless of whether a company&apos;s negligence may have caused the blaze. }}\n{{ r | LAT_2 | p=1 | q=Under state guidelines, a utility or its customers are responsible for paying property damages from wildfires linked to the company&apos;s equipment. With aging infrastructure electrifying remote areas of increasingly hot and dry terrain, the cost and risk have grown significantly in recent years. Pacific Gas & Electric filed for bankruptcy, anticipating some $30 billion in liability for fires in 2017 and 2018, earlier this year. }}\nIn July 2019, a new $21 billion wildfire trust fund was created to pay for damages from future wildfires, started with a 50-50 balance of utility and customer monies and also reduced the liability threshold for utilities to where customers must prove negilgence before companies are held liable.{{ r | LAT_2 | p=1 | q=California&apos;s investor-owned utility companies have agreed to open up their wallets to pay into the state&apos;s wildfire fund in exchange for less financial responsibility when blazes are linked to their equipment. ... The fund, propped up by $21 billion split equally between utility customers and shareholders, is meant to act as a second insurance policy for publicly traded electricity companies and to offset concerns from Wall Street about massive monetary liabilities that have threatened to upend the energy market in California. ... The law takes $10.5 billion from electricity customers through the continuation of a charge on monthly bills that was set to expire next year. In return, wildfire costs that would typically lead to higher bills for customers will instead be paid out by the fund, potentially avoiding price hikes. ... For their $10.5 billion, the utilities are allowed to tap into the fund to pay wildfire damages that exceed insurance coverage. The law also shifts the burden of proof in regulatory proceedings \u2014 another benefit for the utilities \u2014 and requires outside groups to intervene to prove that the company failed to properly manage its system to prevent the fire. }}\n\nCritics of inverse condemnation point out that it can lead to utility bankruptcies which can threaten the integrity of the California power grid as well as hurt financing the states' efforts for renewable energy and against climate change, one of the causes of the intensified fire threat.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bradford |first1=Peter |title=Making PG&E pay more than its fair share of fire damage could backfire on the state |url=https://www.sacbee.com/opinion/california-forum/article212316269.html |work=Sacramento Bee |publisher=McClatchy Company |date=May 31, 2018 |location=Sacramento CA}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to court cases in recent years and the evolution of [[case law]] which have made new standards of legal liability, the [[Government of California|California State]] [[California State Legislature|legislature]] and the [[Governor of California|Governor]]<!-- it take both legislature and governor to enact a law; so action on both sides of the government of california here --> also enacted new [[statutory law]]s to modify the legal regime under which electrical utilities operate in California.  Over 20 new wildfire-related laws were enacted in the 2019 legislative session, several of them affecting the electrical service providing utility companies.<ref name=lat20191002>[https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-02/california-power-shutoffs-new-laws-newsom California adds new rules for planned power shutoffs under laws signed by Newsom], Los Angeles Times, October 2, 2019, accessed October 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Undergrounding==\nThe fire risk from the electricity supply is principally from the large amount of energy carried in [[Overhead power line|above-ground]] power lines, which under fault conditions can become a factor in the [[Fire triangle|ignition]] of wildfires. [[Public utility|Public utilities]] in the state of California have a total of {{convert|26,000| miles}} of high voltage [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] lines, and {{convert|240,000 |miles}} of  [[Electric power distribution|distribution]] lines.  Distribution lines bring electricity directly to homes; two thirds of them statewide are above ground.{{ r | USN_1| p=1 | q=California has 25,526 miles of higher voltage transmission lines, and 239,557 miles of distribution lines, two-thirds of which are overhead, according to CPUC. }}\nFor transmission lines, the cost of constructing these underground is approximately {{USD|80 million}} per mile{{ r | SFC_1 | p=1 | q=Those transmission lines, typically supported by tall, steel-lattice towers, carry electricity at high voltages across long distances. They are far more expensive to place in the ground than the lower-voltage distribution lines that bring electricity directly into residential neighborhoods. \u201cIt makes undergrounding distribution look cheap \u2014 think like $80 million a mile,\u201d Wara said. \u201cYou basically dig a trench and build a building around the transmission line.\u201d PG&E has more than 18,000 miles of transmission lines. }}\nwhile for distribution lines, the construction cost of new underground lines is about {{USD|3 million}} per mile, compared to overhead lines at about $800,000 per mile.{{ r | USN_1| p=1 | q=It costs about $3 million per mile to convert underground electric distribution lines from overhead, while the cost to build a mile of new overhead line is less than a third of that, at approximately $800,000 per mile,... }}\n\nThe state's largest utility, PG&E, has {{convert|107,000 |miles}} of distribution lines, {{convert|81,000 |miles}} of which are overhead.  The cost to convert all of PG&E's overhead distribution lines to underground lines would be approximately {{USD|240 billion}}, or roughly {{USD|15,000}} per PG&E customer. (This cost estimate is only for distribution lines, not the higher voltage transmission lines.){{ r | USN_1| p=1 | q=PG&E, the state&apos;s largest utility, maintains approximately 81,000 miles of overhead distribution lines and approximately 26,000 miles of underground distribution lines. It also has about 18,000 miles of larger transmission lines, the majority of which are overhead lines. At a cost of $3 million per mile, undergrounding 81,000 miles of distribution lines would cost $243 billion. PG&E has 16 million customers; distributing that expense equally would amount to a bill of more than $15,000 per account. }}\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2019}}\n*Several hundred miles to the south of San Francisco, [[San Diego Gas & Electric]] shut off power to approximately 400 customers in eastern [[San Diego County]], California on Friday, October 4, 2019, due to combustion hazards posed by the first [[Santa Ana wind]] event of the fall. {{As of|2019|10|8|df=US}}, SDG&E anticipated restoring power by the following Friday, October 11.<ref name=\"cbs20191008\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs8.com/article/news/local/sdge-warns-of-potential-power-shut-off-across-san-diego-county/509-2a630c51-5c18-40d1-b9ee-b703379f7864|title=SDG&E shuts off power to some East San Diego County residents|website=KFMB|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>{{update after|2019|10|21}}\n*On Wednesday, October 9, around 12 AM PDT, PG&E began to shut off power to many regions, as a pre-emptive measure to help avoid wildfires caused by electric lines.<ref name=\"morris\"/> The shutdown of nearly {{convert|25000|mi|km}} of electric lines was expected to affect more than 2 million people, of PG&E's 16 million total served.  Power was projected to remain off for up to several days after the high winds subside as all of the shutdown lines must be inspected for wind damage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/victim-own-failure-why-pg-235612401.html|title='A victim of their own failure': Why PG&E's massive power shutdown in California was inevitable|website=news.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n*On October 10, SCE cut power to 13,000 customers, (and warned 175,000 of potential power cuts depending on conditions).<ref name=OCR_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.ocregister.com/2019/10/09/map-sce-says-power-outages-could-come-to-these-southern-california-areas/ | title= Map: Where Southern California Edison has cut power or is considering it | last=Johnson | first=Nikie | newspaper=[[Orange County Register]] | date=October 10, 2019 | access-date=October 27, 2019 | archive-url= | archive-date= | url-status=live | pages= | quote=Southern California Edison has shut off power to about 12,900 customers Thursday, Oct. 10, while an area containing almost 174,000 SCE customers is under consideration for power shutoffs as a way to prevent wildfires from starting. }}</ref>\n*By October 11, three days into the pre-emptive blackout, winds had begun to subside and PG&E restored power to some customers, but about 500,000 out of a total of approximately 800,000 still had power cut off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-10/unprecedented-california-blackout-spreads-with-millions-in-dark|title=Unprecedented California Blackout Ending as PG&E Restores Power\n|first=Mark|last=Chediak|date=October 10, 2019|website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref>{{update after|2019|10|20}}<!-- it's October 20 now; is the power shutoff still in force for some???  If it is over, when was it?  And power was restored under what sort of protocol? who got power first?  etc. -->\n\n*On October 22, PG&E was warning of a potential second round of preemptive shutoffs which could affect over 500,000 customers.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/california-pg-e-warns-fresh-145431402.html California: PG&E warns of fresh power shutoffs for 500,000 due to fire weather], October 22, 2019.</ref><!--  -->\n*On October 25, San Diego Gas & Electric had cut power to 19,000 households, potentially rising up to 50,000, in San Diego County because of a combination of high winds, high temperature, and dry conditions.<ref name=MSN_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/weather/topstories/sdg-26e-shutoffs-nearly-19000-without-power-in-san-diego-county/ar-AAJnbu1 | title=SDG&E Shutoffs: Nearly 19,000 Without Power In San Diego County | last= | first= | newspaper=[[MSN]] | date= | access-date=October 27, 2019 | archive-url= | archive-date= | url-status=live | quote=The predicted Santa Ana winds initially prompted San Diego Gas & Electric to notify roughly 24,000 customers of potential power shutoffs for safety reasons, but as of 7 a.m. Friday that number had increased to just over 47,500. }}</ref>\n*On October 26, PG&E announced that it would be shutting off power for 940,000 customers in Northern California, again with the rationale of preventing more wildfires.  This \"is the second major shutoff by PG&E this month.\"<ref name=cnbc20191026>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/26/pge-will-shut-off-power-to-940000-customers-in-northern-california-to-reduce-wildfire-risk.html PG&E will cut power to 940,000 as California wildfires rage: \u2018Most serious weather situation in recent memory\u2019], CNBC, October 26, 2019.</ref>\n*On October 27, over 1 million customers and a total of over 3,000,000 individuals were affected. A total of more than 3 million people across California were without power that day.<ref name=\"Historic Blackout Underway\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/california-wildfires/article/PG-E-outages-Over-3-million-people-blacked-out-14566085.php|title=PG&E outages: Historic blackout underway, 1.3 million in Bay Area without power|first=J. D.|last=Morris|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=October 27, 2019|accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*By October 28, [[Southern California Edison]] had shut off power to 25,000 customers and conducted notifications for up to 350,000 more in 10 counties around the greater Los Angeles area.<ref name=ladn20191028>[https://www.dailynews.com/2019/10/28/power-outage-map-where-southern-california-edison-has-cut-electricity-or-is-considering/ Power outage map: Where Southern California Edison has cut electricity or is considering it], Los Angeles Daily News, October 28, 2019, accessed October 29, 2019.</ref>\n*On November 20, PG&E shut off power to approximately 450,000 individuals in Northern California.<ref name=\"LA Times November\" />\n\n==Impacts==\nA man dependent on an oxygen supply died 12 minutes after the outage started in his area on October 11. An investigation has been initiated.  His family said he could not reach his battery-powered tank in time.{{r|Fox death}} Large numbers of other disabled people reported issues with poor communication by PG&E of when shutoffs would occur, and with the inability to power or charge electrical devices on which their wellbeing depended during shutoffs. Affected devices included ventilators, oxygen concentrators, nebulizers, dialysis machines, refrigerators for drugs such as insulin, and electrically powered beds, hoists and wheelchairs. PG&E had a list of over 30,000 customers registered on their Medical Baseline program as being vulnerable to shutoffs, but used it only as a contact list, leaving the affected disabled customers unsupported. Dependence on the Medical Baseline list meant PG&E inevitably missing many more disabled people not registered with the program. Others who were registered reported they were not contacted. PG&E also refused to give many local counties access to the Medical Baseline list, leaving them unable to check on vulnerable residents. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/11/california-pge-utility-power-shutoff-disabled</ref> <ref>http://www.capradio.org/articles/2019/12/02/pge-withheld-information-about-medically-at-risk-customers-ahead-of-major-power-shutoff/</ref>\n\nUnder [[backup power]] on October 11, 2019 [UTC], the Mission Operations Center (MOC) at the [[Space Sciences Laboratory]] at [[University of California, Berkeley]] oversaw the deployment of a [[Ionospheric Connection Explorer|satellite]] launched from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]]. Paula Milano, who helps run the Laboratory, did not want to postpone the launch saying \u201cIf a scrub of the mission happens because of Berkeley, that's a huge black eye for us, and it's a huge public black eye for [[NASA]].\u201d After notification on October 7, the lab began extensive preparation for the power outage.{{r|Wired}}\n\nBy late October, water had been restricted for some{{clarify|extent? how many affected? by what water-providing agencies?  or companies?|date=November 2019}} in areas which rely on pump stations.<ref name=\"Mercury News\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/10/29/power-shutdown-do-you-have-to-pay-pge-plus-other-questions-answered/|title=Power shutdown: Do you have to pay PG&E, plus other questions answered|first=Levi|last=Sumagaysay|date=October 29, 2019|accessdate=October 29, 2019|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref>{{update after|2019|11|6|df=US}}<!-- and then what?  was it restricted for a few days?  weeks?  has it been restored? -->\n\n[[Sonoma\u2013Marin Area Rail Transit]] [[commuter rail]] services were cancelled on October 28<ref>{{cite web |title=Service Advisory: All Trains Canceled for Monday, October 28 |url=http://www.sonomamarintrain.org/node/333 |publisher=SMART |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> and 29<ref>{{cite web |title=Service Advisory: All Trains Canceled for Tuesday, October 30 |url=http://www.sonomamarintrain.org/node/334 |publisher=SMART |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> due to loss of power at [[Level crossing|crossings]] throughout the system. Partial service as far north as Downtown [[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]] was restored the following day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Smart Train Service Running On Limited Schedule Wednesday Through Nov. 6. |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/bayarea/article/Smart-Train-Service-Running-On-Limited-Schedule-14572872.php |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |agency=Bay City News Service |publisher=SFGate |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Potential fires averted==\n\nAfter the early October power shutoffs, the CEO of PG&E stated that they found more than 100 cases of \"wind-related damage\" to the 25,000 miles of power lines they had de-energized. {{ r | SFC_PGE_statement }} He also stated \"More than half of PG&E\u2019s 70,000-square-mile service area in Northern and Central California is considered by state officials to be at high risk of wildfire.  In 2012, that designation applied to just 15% of our service area.\" {{ r | SFC_PGE_statement }}\n\nBy the end of October, PG&E officials told a federal judge that the power shutoffs so far helped prevent up to 56 wildfires. This was mostly caused by problems in previous inspections of power lines.<ref>{{cite news |title=PG&E Says 56 Fires Could Have Been Sparked Without Mass Shutoffs This Month |url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/pge-says-56-fires-could-have-been-sparked-without-mass-shutoffs-this-month/2054726/ |accessdate=21 April 2020 |agency=NBC Bay Area |date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019 California wildfires]]\n* [[List of California wildfires]]\n* [[List of major power outages]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Wired\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/icon-launch-blackout/|title=UC Berkeley Was About to Launch a Satellite. Then PG&E Said It Was Cutting Power|work=Wired|first=Matt |last=Simon|date=October 17, 2019|access-date=October 19, 2019|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=LAT_1 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-wildfire-liability-law-gavin-newsom-legislature-20190529-story.html | title=Newsom and legislative leaders decline to embrace changes to California\u2019s wildfire liability law | last=Luna | first=Taryn | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=May 29, 2019 | access-date=October 16, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602055944/https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-wildfire-liability-law-gavin-newsom-legislature-20190529-story.html | archive-date=June 2, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=LAT_2 >{{ cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-25/california-utilities-agree-to-pay-10-5-billion-into-new-wildfire-fund| title=California utilities agree to pay $10.5 billion into new wildfire fund  | last=Luna | first=Taryn | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | | date=July 25, 2019 | access-date=October 16, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801003122/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-